definition.value: A dipeptide composed of L-threonine and L-tyrosine joined by a peptide linkage.
A reagent used to couple amino acids during artificial peptide synthesis.
An L-lysine derivative in which one of the amino hydrogens at N(6)-amino is substituted by a 6-[(2S)-2-amino-2-carboxyethyl]-3,4-dioxocyclohexa-1,5-dien-1-yl group.
An L-tryptophan derivative that is L-tryptophan-6,7-dione in which a cysteine unit is attached at position 4 via its side-chain thiol group.
A tripeptide composed of L-tryptophan, L-alanine, and L-aspartic acid joined by a peptide linkage.
A nucleotide-sugar oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups of cyclic ADP-beta-D-ribose.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of (S)-alpha-hydroxyglutaric acid-gamma-lactone, obatined by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
An organophosphate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of carbamoyl adenylate, obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate group.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the four amino groups of 6''-O-carbamoylkanamycin A.
A monohydroxy-5beta-cholanic acid in which the hydroxy group is located at the 7alpha-position. A structural derivative of the bile acid, chenodeoxycholic acid.
A butan-4-olide obtained by formal intramolecular condensation between the 2-hydroxy and 4-carboxy groups of (S)-2-hydroxyglutaric acid
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the five amino groups of tobramycin.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the five amino groups of nebramycin 5'.
A purine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is AMP in which one of the phosphate OH groups substituted by a carbamoyl group
A ketoaldonolactone obtained by formal intramolecular condensation between the carboxy group and the 4-hydroxy group of L-xylo-hex-2-ulonic acid.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosohate and carboxy groups of L-threonylcarbamoyladenylate.
A carbamoylkanamycin that is kanamycin A bearing a single carbamoyl substituent located at position 6'' (on the 3-aminoglucose ring).
Any kanamycin carrying one or more carbamoyl substituents
A glutamine derivative with an acetyl group bound at the alpha-amino group.
A carbamoylkanamycin that is tobramycin bearing a single carbamoyl substituent located at position 6'' (on the 3-aminoglucose ring).
A threonine derivative that is L-threonine in which one of the amino hydrogens is substituted by and adenyloxycarbonyl group
A dipeptide composed of N-acetyl-L-aspartic acid and L-glutamic acid joined by a peptide linkage.
The fatty acid methyl ester of isobutyric acid.
An L-alpha-amino acid which is biosynthesised from erythrose 4-phosphate and phosphoenolpyruvate (i.e. phenylalanine, tyrosine, and tryptophan). A closed class.
A tripeptide composed of L-tryptophan, L-alanine, and glycine joined by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of L-tryptophan, L-aspartic acid, and L-serine joined by peptide linkages.

A carbonyl compound produced as a water-soluble byproduct when fatty acids are broken down for energy in the liver. There are three endogenous ketone bodies: acetone, acetoacetic acid, and (R)-3-hydroxybutyric acid; others may be produced as a result of the metabolism of synthetic triglycerides.
A dipeptide formed from L-tryptophan and L-serine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-tyrosine and L-histidine residues.
A tripeptide composed of L-valine and two L-proline units joined by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of L-valine, L-asparagine, and L-proline joined by peptide linkages.
A dipeptide formed from L-valine and L-asparagine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-valine and glycine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-valine and L-histidine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-valine and L-proline residues.
A chemical substance that is an organic compound or mixture of compounds that is composed of long-chain molecules and is malleable at ambient temperatures.
A dipeptide formed from L-valine and L-tyrosine residues.
A dipeptide formed from two L-valine residues.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the gamma-carboxy group of glutamic acid with the amino group of another glutamic acid.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of the two carboxy goups of bromosuccinic acid.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the gamma-carboxy group of glutamic acid with the amino group of glutamine

A macrolide antibiotic that is erythromycin A in which the ketone group has been converted into the corresponding imine and then reduced to give the corresponding amino compound (the 9S diastereoisomer).
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of (S)-2-hydroxybutyric acid, obtained by decarboxylation of the carboxy group.
A dipeptide formed from L-tryptophan and L-alanine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-valine and L-asparagine residues.
A dicarboxylic acid that is succinic acid substituted at position 2 by a bromine atom.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is nonane with two  carboxylic acid groups at positions C-1 and C-9.
An ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the amino group of dipivefrin.
